BoCom, Posco, Samsung Electronics: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-05-30T21:45:15Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/bocom-posco-samsung-electronics-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Bank of Communications Co. (601328 CH): Bank of Taiwan said
it signed an agreement with Bank of Communications to cooperate
on loans, trade financing and personnel training. BoCom, as
 China ’s fifth-largest lender is also known, climbed 0.7 percent
to 5.73 yuan.  BDO Leasing & Finance Inc. (BLFI)  : The unit of the
largest Philippine bank by assets will broaden its loan
portfolio and targets a “double-digit” increase in profit this
year, a stock-exchange filing showed. The stock fell 2.4 percent
to 1.61 pesos on May 27.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  : The world’s largest mining
company said it has suspended production at its Kwinana nickel
refinery near Perth,  Australia , because of a shortage of
hydrogen supply. The plant will resume operations in early June,
Kelly Quirke, a spokeswoman for the Melbourne-based company said
by telephone. BHP slipped 0.5 percent to A$43.91.  First Philippine Holdings Corp. (FPH)  : The company,
which has investments in power generation, is “evaluating”
options to refinance its debts to “take advantage of a
favorable  debt market ,” Chief Finance Officer Francis Giles
Puno said. First Philippine may use its cash to buy back shares
and reduce debt, he also said. The stock was unchanged at 63
pesos.  KNM Group Bhd. (KNMG)  : The Malaysian oil and gas
services provider scrapped a $350 million exchangeable bond sale,
according to a statement to the Kuala Lumpur stock exchange. KNM
Group fell 2.3 percent to 2.10 ringgit.  Posco (005490 KS): South Korea’s biggest steelmaker plans
to sell 41 billion yen of bonds exchangeable into American
depositary receipts of SK Telecom Co. (017670 KS), according to
a regulatory filing.  Posco (005490)  fell 1.2 percent to 431,500 won and
SK Telecom, South Korea’s largest mobile-phone company, slid 0.6
percent to 160,000 won.  Samsung Electronics Co. (005930 KS): Asia’s biggest maker
of chips, flat screens and mobile phones will begin mass
production at its liquid crystal display plant in Suzhou, China,
in the first half of 2013, the company said in an e-mailed
statement. Samsung slipped 0.8 percent to 884,000 won.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
 bmoestafa@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
